node.text:
Cooking up some #boletusrubriceps and #boletusbarrowsii for breakfast! Really fun to combine these two types of boletes for breakfast, along with some N’juda (spicy spreadable salami), padron/shishito peppers, onions, and green beans (all from my garden). Also made a quick French style omelette seasoned with porcini powder and truffle butter. A seriously tasty nutritious breakfast with some lions mane mocha coffee. 
.

node.text:
Cooking up some Lions Mane mushrooms with my faux-rizo mycoprotein mix, shallots, corn, zucchini, deglazing with Sherry, adding cream, reducing. Simmered some @primeroots lobster ravioli then added them to the sauce to finish cooking. Finished off with basil, arugula, Pecorino, and pepper.
.
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
Check out these beautiful porcini buttons peeking out from the forest floor. This is the #SpringPorcini or #Boletusrexveris, a large fleshy Bolete related to the classic King Bolete (Boletus edulis). This species fruits in California from ~3000-7000 feet under pine (Pinus) and fir (Abies), also at lower elevations up in Oregon. They are similar in texture and flavor to other porcini, with a pleasant mild mushroom flavor and meaty texture. 
.
As with other porcini I find them a little bit bitter if cooked straight up in a pan. My preferred way to cook them is to chop and cook in 1/4 inch of water, cooking off all the water, then removing the mushrooms from the pan and cleaning off the browned bits (this is where the bitterness is concentrated for me). Whole roasting in tin foil is another way to prep them with bitterness, but this works best with younger specimens. My favorite prep for Kings is to dry and powder them. The drying process adds a deep and savory umami notes to the porcini flavor. The powder is my secret ingredient in many dishes, adding amazing mushroom nuance to virtually everything I cook. 
.
This was a pretty rough year for finding spring mushrooms, but I’m grateful for the few good clusters that I did find. Hope you guys enjoy my explanation and little bit of ASMR as I clean/trim them up.
.

node.text:
Had a fantastic chat with Forrest Valkai (@renegadescienceteacher) about science communication and hominid evolution. We get into his Masters work on Homo erectus and tracking the climate they lived in. We talk about the “Stoned Ape Theorm” and how it over simplifies the evolution on humans. We chat about hypotheses and how the scientific method requires an open critical mind. We chat about human nutrition, the benefits of eating mushrooms, and Forrest’s favorite prep for mushrooms. It was a pleasure to chat with one of my favorite science communicators, check out his website RenegadeScienceTeacher.com to learn more!
.

.
.

node.text:
Quickly assembling some rice straw wine cap beds. My process is to soak the straw for 3-4 days in water and let it anerobically ferment (to reduce fungal competition) then inoculate with #WineCap #Strophariarugosoannulata spawn. Straw is an easy substrate for wine caps and should produce a large flush of mushrooms quickly (2-3 months) if watered regularly and kept in the shade. This is a low tech lazy method, but it works for me. Kiddie pools have drainage holes poked into them, placed atop a palate to help with airflow. Fingers crossed, this batch turns out well. Thanks again to @northsporemushrooms for the wine cap grain spawn. You can save 10% on your order from NorthSpore.com with discount code “FASCINATEDBYFUNGI”. Cheers!
.
Also, that awesome yellow t-shirt I’m wearing is one of @yellowelanor’s, check out her Patreon and Etsy!

I start by talking about why I spank the boletes (it’s a density thing), then get into cutting up butter boletes and oyster mushrooms I grew from a @nearbynaturals kit. I throw all my mushies in a pan with a 1/4 of water and get them cooking, then I slice a butter Bolete thickly for a raw carpaccio prep with my Dad’s tarragon vinegar, really good olive oil, kosher & maldon salts, and kampot pepper. Then I add all my ingredients to my lazy pizza casserole and bake it, check my story to see the end result.

node.text:
Had a fantastic chat with Jaeki, a man of many talents. He’s worked for major music magazines (XXL), hung out with famous rappers, produced his own documentary on Netflix (@BadRapFilm), and has a street ware brand (@alumniofny). He’s a voice for promoting small business in and around Queens/NYC. He’s a prominent activist in the AAPI community and speaks to the Asian American experience. We get into the weeds on all sorts of topics, covering food, travel (Oaxaca/Mexico City), mushrooms, environmental sustainability, and more. Truly a pleasure to chat with Jaeki.
.
.
.

node.text:
Many thanks to Kristen (@kaydubsthehikingscientist) for chatting with me about fungal plant pathogens (and Oomycetes which aren’t technically fungi), entomophathic fungi (zombie cicadas), the reality of being a scientist on social media, and ways in which we can partner with fungi to help mitigate the woes of the world. Always a pleasure to talk to Kristen. I learn so much from her and am thoroughly entertained everytime. To hear more from Kristen, check out her Patreon and follow her here on IG.
.
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
Happy Slime Mold Sunday! Check out this sublime aggregation of slime bubbles. At this point in the development of slime mold sporangia (the spire dispersal structures) it’s hard to differentiate species, but given the structure of this, my best guess is that it is a #Tubifera species (although I’m open to suggestions). 
.
Slime molds are not fungi, but instead Protista (like an Ameoba). They are single celled organisms that merge into a giant cell that consumes organic material until it forms beautiful sporangia to disperse its spores and start the life cycle over again. I saw this beautiful tanish pinky slime around the forests of Colorado; really fun to see a different species in a different state.
.
.
.
.
.
.
#slimemold #slimemoldsunday #myxomycetes #slimemould #slimemoldsunday

node.text:
Happy Fungus Friday! I’m home from Colorado, but still buzzing with excitement at all of the amazing fungi I found. Beyond all of the incredible boletes, I found loads of these massive and seriously impressive #HawksWing #ScalyHedgehog or #Sarcodonimbraticus. These are mycorrhizal mushrooms that grow in association with pine and spruce (in Colorado), but can occur with other tree species in different parts of the country. They have distinctive “shingles” or scabers on the cap, giving it a winged appearance. They are unmistakable because of their distinctive teeth or spines underneath the cap, an evolutionary adaptation to disperse spores (as opposed to using pores or gills). These mushrooms are extremely solid and can last for many weeks, most likely they contain a number of bioactive compounds that help them resists rot and molds.
.
These mushrooms are edible, but somewhat controversial. They are highly regarded by some for their dense meaty texture and nutty umami flavor, but also have a reputation for being bitter. I really enjoyed eating the Colorado version of the species, but did notice that some of the older specimens had a slight bitter note. I really liked slicing up this mushroom, marinating with oil/herbs/seasoning, then grilling (as suggested by @foragecolorado). The taste of this was very different from the Sarcodon species I have collected in Napa, which are some of the most unpalatably bitter things I’ve ever tried in my life. This mushroom can also be dried and powdered to make a delicious seasoning. It is a popular edible mushroom in Korea and Japan, not sure which species grows in Asia.
.
There is probably more species diversity of this mushroom in North America than is covered by just the S. imbraticus species designation. European collections are now recognized as S. squamosus. The Norwegian collections have been used to make a blue green dye for fabrics. 
Hope you guys have a great weekend!
.
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

Having an absolute blast experiencing the Colorado Summer Mushroom season. Thanks a particularly wet year, conditions are perfect for mushrooms. Up around 9000ft in the mountains near Denever we ran into a fantastic biodiversity of beautiful mushrooms. It’s so cool to experience a mushroom season that is similar in progression to what I see in California, but at a completely different time of year. I love that the sequential progression of species is similar, just offset by ~6 months.
.
I’ve been really impressed by the huge solid Boletus rubriceps, they are by far my favorite “porcini” species I have tasted (no significant bitterness for me). I love the orange colored caps of the Aspen boletes and how it contrasts with the beautiful Aspen bark and leaves. The massive Hawks Wings it Sarcodon have also been a joy to find and cook. So seriously impressed by the selection of fungi out here.
.
Thanks to Zach from @mushroomcultpro for hanging out with me and showing his state.
.
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
Rocky Mountain Kings! Took my first foray into the summer mushroom season here in Colorado and found a bevy of #RockyMountainReds or #Boletusrubriceps. Very similar to other #KingBolete species, this is a large flesh mycorrhizal mushroom with pores that go from white to yellow to brown as they mature. They have distinctive ruby red caps that fade tawny brown with age. The reticulation on the stipe is particularly pronounced and absolutely gorgeous (check out all the photos). This species grows in the southern Rocky Mountains in association with Englemann Spruce and possibly fir and pine as well. 
.
As with other boletes, they fruit at similar times as Amanita muscaria and the large Hawks Wing Sarcodons (shingled hedgehogs). Boletus rubriceps are large and fleshy, a very tasty mushroom with great flavor fresh or dried. Hoping I get a chance to dry some of these and fly them home with me.
.
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
Celebrating my birthday with a “Sporesplosion”! Check out this #puffball unexpectedly exploding it’s spores all over me. Puffballs are common white balls of fungus that grow commonly in fields (amongst grasses) and in woodlands. They are “gasteroid” mushrooms, meaning the spores develop on the inside of the fruiting body (rather than at gills/pores). Initially puffballs are all white inside, at this point they are delicious edibles (think savory marshmallow). As they mature the inside turns yellow to dark brown and eventually into a dry powdery mass of spores. The mature puffball develops a hole in the top that allows spores to escape when the fruiting body is disturbed (usually by a falling rain drop).
.
After posting puffball videos online, I’ve seen a myriad of reactions. Many people are nostalgic for childhood fun of stomping poofing the puffballs (Lycoperdon literally translates to “wolf farts”), while others are fearful thanks to the featuring of spores as harbingers of doom in prominent Sci-Fi (Halo, Last of Us, Alien: Covenant, Prometheus, etc…). Despite the association of spores with danger, the amount of spores you accidentally inhale while messing with a puffball are probably nothing to worry about (unless you have a compromised immune system). Intentionally inhaling spores can be very bad for you, a recent internet trend of inhaling puffballs (think cinnamon challenge but with a mushroom) landed a number of people in the hospital with respiratory issues. Like I said, I don’t intentionally inhale spores, but I’m not worried about starting an alien/zombie invasion if I accidentally inhale a few. Hope you guys enjoy the surprise “Sporesplosion”, yes that’s me snorting and giggling out of amusement.
.
.
.
.
.
,

As I’ve said before, it was a unusually dry spring alpine season here in California. Normally these little orange goobers are fat and swollen, looking every bit like their name, the #AlpineJellyCone or #Guepiniopsisalpina. Unfortunately these normally delightful orange were rather lean looking this year, well on their way to being dried out. They are small gelatinous brown rot fungi that grow commonly on conifer is mountainous habitats, common near snow melt. They related to Dacrymyces, which also grow on conifer, distinct from Tremella which prefer parasitizing Stereum on hard woods. 
.
Hope you enjoy these cute little #forbiddensnacks despite not being quite as plump as other years. 
.
.
.
.
.

node.text:
Happy Fungus Friday! It’s been an exceptionally dry year and the spring season was generally disappointing. One of my few bright spots was finding this absolutely perfect pair of porcini hiding beneath a decaying log. These are the same #SpringKings #Boletusrexvervis that I posted about earlier in the week. Mycorrhizal with Pinus and Abies, fruiting in the Sierra and Cascade mountains from spring to summer ~3000-7000ft. They are a choice edible mushroom, especially when young and crispy like this.
.
Since it was a lean year for porcini, I had to savor the ones I did find. This pair was particularly impressive, super solid and crisp, with dense resonance. I have really come to enjoy the ASMR aspects of cleaning up my mushrooms. Especially the crispy slicing at the end, trimming the base of the stem back into the soil and covering it back up (my version of best practices, don’t @ me for not “cutting” the mushroom). 
.
This poor mushroom season isn’t a fluke, it’s a function of climate change. Weather patterns are changing faster than we can understand. The effects of global climate change are accelerating in scary and unpredictable ways (see the recent heat wave in the PNW/BC). It’s not too late change stop the catastrophic extinction event we are heading for, but we need to start taking this seriously. Now is the time to invest fully in sustainable green energy and completely divest from fossil fuels. We desperately need to sink carbon back into the soil, mushrooms are some of our best allies. It’s going to take a coordinated global effort to fix our problems, not sure if or how that is possible, but we need to do something or scary dry fire years like 2021 will become the norm on the west coast. Extreme changes are coming, but Nature can help us buffer them if we stop destroying it.

Check out these neat looking baskets full of steely grey eggs, this is a kind of #BirdsNestFungi known as #Cyathus. They are saprobic mushrooms, growing on dead wood. They start out covered by a gelatinous membrane that is worn away by rain. Falling rain drops can displace the egg like “peridioles”, helping to spread the spores of this mushroom. Cyathus can be differentiated from other Birds Nest Fungi by their dark/grey eggs and striated cups.
.
These small #SplashCup fungi are common on wood chip beds, often fruiting in prolific numbers. They are easy to miss with the naked eye, it’s only when you get close that you realize the microcosms that exist hidden amongst the mulch. 
.
The fruiting bodies can persist for weeks to months and contain some interesting bioactive molecules that deter the growth of bacteria and molds. It has also been hypothesized that these mushrooms contain photoreceptors (proteins that sense light) as light is required for fruiting body formation and the cups will orient towards a light source. Pretty cool for little tiny fungi that you might otherwise miss.
.
Birds Nest Fungi are some of my favorites. So easy to over look, but so hard to forget. Hope you guys enjoy these pics from my trip to Kentucky (see on WKU campus).
